column3: SK Stones has always set itself apart from its competitors. It is home to the most exceptional and finest Natural Stones from around the world. Commitment to quality, innovation and uniqueness continues to be at our core and we believe that our variety and expertise will be telling factors in our growth. Established in 1993, SK Stones is the pioneer in introducing imported stones. In 1996, SK Stones emerged as the best marble selling unit for the domestic market. Ever since it’s inception in 1993, remark‐able projects have been executed both locally and internationally. Through vision, strategic direction, and unwavering commitment, SK Stones has emerged as a premium stone and marble exporter, with a diversified international business portfolio. We remain resolutely committed in offering the best quality and prompt delivery of exclusive materials, along with limitless selection. Our team knows that marble is nature and it is hard to emulate and deliver nature. But, at SK Stones, we take that as a challenge, and we love challenges.

column1: Italian white marbles which have been in demand for all high end homes are still holding their demand . For decades these have been WOW factor for any project. When Quartz started they picked up market share however like any other man made product they started losing value. Now no matter what type of Quartz someone uses its always considered as economical product more than anything else. Moreover now there are sealants available in market which makes natural Stone surface very strong and have absorbtion.
These days there are Quartz slabs which hover in same price range as of Italian Cararra marble. However any project that has been done with marble is considered more valuable than any Quartz.

Quartz is still holding its spot reason being its easy to fabricate and its uniform in color. When we talk of no color variation that's not preference of  high end designers. Most of the times designers prefer to have natural movements and natural characteristic which make them unique and reflect natures gift for everyone.

Massimo having 30 years of experience is second generation in Stone business.  ",,2020-03-31,page,https://skstonesusa.com/blog/,https://skstonesusa.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/cor059.jpg,cor059,,,,https://skstonesusa.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/cor059.jpg,,publish,3,nouman,nouman.muhd@gmail.com,Muhammad,Nouman,blog,,elementor_header_footer,0,0,60,closed,closed,2020-06-17

2623,Porcelain,"

Porcelain provides a worry-free luxury lifestyle to all your favorite rooms. We import the highest quality Italian Porcelain tile designed to add limitless style through endless designer patterns, textures, and color possibilities. Porcelain in your room lets you enjoy long lasting beautiful floors without the stress of excessive maintenance. This is the choice of flooring to bring beauty into the spaces you actually live in.

column3: Transform your space into a nature getaway with the wood look porcelain collection inspired by the wild.
Capture the energy of the big city lifestyle into your home with our urban rustic porcelain.
Broad, yet subtle; practical yet inspiring: the refined look of crisp, polished porcelain removes any sense of clutter from your most important spaces.
Invite a sense of the timeless into your home and let mother nature’s most fearsome design become your bedrock.

column1: 2680,"Privacy Policy","<pre>This privacy policy has been compiled to better serve those who are concerned with how their ""Personally identifiable information"" (PII) is being used online. PI is information that can be used on its own or with other information to identify, contact, or locate a single person, or to identify an individual in context. Please read our privacy policy carefully to get a clear understanding of how we collect, use, protect or otherwise handle your Personally Identifiable Information in accordance with our website.
What personal information do we collect from the people that visit our blog, website or app?
When ordering or registering on our site, as appropriate, you may be asked to enter your name, email address, mailing address, phone number or other details to help you with your experience.
We collect information from you when you register on our site, subscribe to a newsletter, fill out a form or enter information on our site.

We may use the information we collect from you when you register, make a purchase, sign up for our newsletter, respond to a survey or marketing communication, surf the website, or use certain other site features in the following ways:
To personalize your experience and to allow us to deliver the type of content and product offerings in which you are most interested.
To improve our website in order to better serve you.
To allow us to better service you in responding to your customer service requests.
To administer a contest, promotion, survey or other site feature.
To ask for ratings and reviews of services or products
To follow up with them after correspondence (live chat, email or phone inquiries)

Your personal information is contained behind secured networks and is only accessible by a limited number of persons who have special access rights to such systems, and are required to keep the information confidential. In addition, all sensitive/credit information you supply is encrypted via Secure Socket Layer (SSL) technology.
We implement a variety of security measures when a user enters, submits, or accesses their information to maintain the safety of your personal information.
All transactions are processed through a gateway provider and are not stored or processed on our servers.

Yes. Cookies are small files that a site or its service provider transfers to your computer’s hard drive through your Web browser (if you allow) that enables the site’s or service provider’s systems to recognize your browser and capture and remember certain information. For instance, we use cookies to help us remember and process the items in your shopping cart. They are also used to help us understand your preferences based on previous or current site activity, which enables us to provide you with improved services. We also use cookies to help us compile aggregate data about site traffic and site interaction so that we can offer better site experiences and tools in the future.

Compile aggregate data about site traffic and site interactions in order to offer better site experiences and tools in the future. We may also use trusted third-party services that track this information on our behalf.

<pre>You can choose to have your computer warn you each time a cookie is being sent, or you can choose to turn off all cookies. You do this through your browser settings. Since browser is a little different, look at your browser’s Help Menu to learn the correct way to modify your cookies.

If you turn cookies off, Some of the features that make your site experience more efficient may not function properly.It won’t affect the user’s experience that make your site experience more efficient and may not function properly.

We do not sell, trade, or otherwise transfer to outside parties your Personally Identifiable Information unless we provide users with advance notice. This does not include website hosting partners and other parties who assist us in operating our website, conducting our business, or serving our users, so long as those parties agree to keep this information confidential. We may also release information when it’s release is appropriate to comply with the law, enforce our site policies, or protect ours or others’ rights, property or safety.
However, non-personally identifiable visitor information may be provided to other parties for marketing, advertising, or other uses.

Occasionally, at our discretion, we may include or offer third-party products or services on our website. These third-party sites have separate and independent privacy policies. We therefore have no responsibility or liability for the content and activities of these linked sites. Nonetheless, we seek to protect the integrity of our site and welcome any feedback about these sites.

When it comes to the collection of personal information from children under the age of 13 years old, the Children’s Online Privacy Protection Act (COPPA) puts parents in control. The Federal Trade Commission, United States’ consumer protection agency, enforces the COPPA Rule, which spells out what operators of websites and online services must do to protect children’s privacy and safety online.
We do not specifically market to children under the age of 13 years old.
Do we let third-parties, including ad networks or plug-ins collect PII from children under 13?

The Fair Information Practices Principles form the backbone of privacy law in the United States and the concepts they include have played a significant role in the development of data protection laws around the globe. Understanding the Fair Information Practice Principles and how they should be implemented is critical to comply with the various privacy laws that protect personal information.
In order to be in line with Fair Information Practices we will take the following responsive action, should a data breach occur:
We will notify you via email

<pre>We also agree to the Individual Redress Principle which requires that individuals have the right to legally pursue enforceable rights against data collectors and processors who fail to adhere to the law. This principle requires not only that individuals have enforceable rights against data users, but also that individuals have recourse to courts or government agencies to investigate and/or prosecute non-compliance by data processors.
If at any time you would like to unsubscribe from receiving future emails, you can email us at
Follow the instructions at the bottom of each email.
info@opustone.com and we will promptly remove you from ALL correspondence.
If there are any questions regarding this privacy policy, you may contact us using the information below.

column3: We at SK Stones carry over 300 colors of slabs, that includes Marble, Granite, Quartzite, Onyx, Limestone, Soapstone, Calcite, Porcelain and Agates.

column6: They are over 50 different colors of Quartz available at our locations!

column13: Is Onyx a good choice for countertops?

column6: Being a translucent stone, Onyx is more popularly used for bar and bathroom countertops, as it gives a very warm feeling to the room.

column13: How Much Do Granite Countertops Cost?

column6: Especially with natural stones, prices may vary. For example, colorful materials such as blues and greens may cost more than colors like black or white. With that being said prices fluctuate between $35 to $75 per square foot

column13: Which is the common material for floor?

column6: Porcelain tile is the most used material for floors. It looks like wood and marbles. The thickness usually is between 9 to 10 mm.

column13: Which is the most popular material for countertops?

column6: If you are looking for a natural stone countertops, the most common option are granite and quartzite. On the other hand, if you are looking for a man-made material, quartz will be the most popular one.

column13: Does quartzite stain easily?

column6: There are different types of quartzite. Some are more stain-resistant then others. Quartzite is not stain proof, but most quartzite is stain resistant.

column13: Dos heat damage granite countertops?

column6: Granite countertop are heat resistance and can resist to the heat of hot pots without damage.

column13: Where is porcelain tile best utilized?

column6: Porcelain has long durability, it does well in high-traffic spaces. Such as, bathroom, kitchen, and common areas like living room.

column13: Is porcelain difficult to maintain?

column6: No, porcelain is known as one of the easiest material to maintain.

column13: Should quartz be sealed?

column6: Quartz does not require any sealing. Quartz countertops are really flexible and less likely to chip or crack.

column13: What are the disadvantages of quartz countertops?

column6: A disadvantage of quartz is that it cannot be used outside because the long term sunlight exposure will damage the surface.

column13: Is Marble easy to break?

column6: Marble tends to have tiny air channels within its structure, is not a strong type of stone. It could break, chip or crack, but it can be unpredictable.

column13: Does water stain marble?

column6: Marble is consider softer than other natural stones. If not wiped up immediately, water spots and hard water accumulations occur, leaving unsightly stains.

column13: Is white quartz hard to maintain?

column6: A white quartz countertop is very easy to maintain. Quartz countertops are hygienic and have antibacterial properties.

column13: Why is Marble so popular?

column6: Marble is very resistance to extreme heat, it has the lowest maintenance, highest beauty option for a kitchen countertop. People love the versatility of marble

column13: Does quartzite scratch easily?

column6: No, quartzite is popular not only because of its durability, hardness, resistance to heat, scratches, and water absorption, but also because it looks a lot like marble and has granite like properties.

column13: Why is quartzite so expensive?

column6: Quartzite is considered a luxury stone. It takes more time to cut it and extract the blocks from the quarry, because is harder and more abrasive. It also needs more diamond blades, diamonds wires, and diamond polishing heads, etc., which results in higher cost of inputs.

column13: Is quartzite resistant to the UV rays?

column6: Quartzite is highly resistant to UV rays. It is great if you’re using it in an outdoor setting.

column13: Is porcelain tile slippery when wet?

column6: Porcelain tile floors are very slippery. You can avoid slips long before you even purchase the tile. There is a reliable way to know how slippery floor tile will be under both wet and dry conditions: COF (coefficient of friction) slip ratings published by tile manufacturers.

column13: Is Quartz a versatile material?

column6: Yes, because of its durability and variety of colors and designs quartz is considered a versatile material. It is a fantastic material not only for kitchen countertops but also for bathrooms, fireplaces and bars.

column13: Do all stone countertops have to be sealed?

column6: Some stone does not require sealing; however, it is recommended to seal porous stone countertops. Like, marble, limestone, sandstone, and onyx. Sometimes also granite has to be sealed. For quartz, sealing is not required.

column13: What porous means for natural stones?

column6: Pores are little holes in the stones. Those tiny holes allow air, liquid, etc.  to penetrate and be absorbed into the stones.

column13: Is porcelain a natural stone?

column6: No, porcelain is a manufactured product. which is created to mimic the look of natural stones.

column13: Do I have to seal mosaic tiles?

column6: Yes! You have to seal them using products that will protect the tile surface and grout line. Some people recommend sealing a mosaic before and after fixing.

column13: Why is granite good for my home?

column6: Granite is great for your home because it is durable, easy to care for, has a wide variety to choose from, is versatile, and beautiful.

column13: Can you polish granite on your own?

column6: Yes you can! You may also opt to hire a professional for the job, but polishing granite can also be a DIY job.

column13: Do you have to seal porcelain?

column6: The surface of most of porcelain tile does not need to be sealed, although some require a light application of a penetrating sealer to fill the micro pores on the surface of the tile.

column13: Is Onyx good for shower walls?

column6: Yes, Onyx is good for shower walls panes and bathtub walls.

column13: Does Porcelain break easily?

column6: Porcelain is chip and crack resistant, however, if handle them improperly they can break.

column13: Where can you use travertine?

column6: Travertine can be use in Kitchen, fireplace panes, sinks, shower.

column13: Does marble have to be sealed?

column6: Since marble is quite porous, air and liquids can be absorbed into it. This is why sealing is recommended in areas such as the kitchen or bathroom.

column13: What's the best way to clean marble?

column6: Use a soft cloth and warm water with dish soap. Then use a fresh damp cloth to wipe away the soap. Repeat this step until all of the soap is gone. After that, make sure to dry the marble since sitting water can lead to stains.

column13: Does marble chip easily?

column6: Marble is a softer stone than other natural stones. So, banging heavy objects such as pots and pans could lead to chips on the corner of the countertop.

column13: Why does marble turn yellow?

column6: Marble can turn yellow when exposed to water for long periods of time. Sitting liquids can leave unsightly stains on the marble.

column13: Can you cut directly on top of marble countertops?

column6: No, marble is softer than other stones thus can easily get scratched,

column13: What is the green bloom effect?

column6: Chemicals in super glue and acetone or nail polish removers can leave a green stain on granite. This green stain is known as the “green bloom effect.”

column13: Will my stone installation have visible seams?

column6: Most installations of stone do require a seam, however you can discuss the design and layout of the seam with your fabricator.

column13: How is marble formed?

column6: Marble is a metamorphic rock that is formed when limestone is pressurized under intense heat. This crystallizes limestone into a denser rock. Surrounding minerals impact the color of the stone.

column13: Are cracks on the surface normal?

column6: Minute, small cracks like patterns are a normal feature of natural stones. Sealing your marble can prevent any further cracks caused by moisture or foot traffic

column13: Can marble tile be repaired if its damaged?

column6: Marble can be repaired in many cases. Mostly, an epoxy glue or filler is used to repair the damage.

column13: Is bar top in porcelain stain resistant?

column6:
Porcelain is high stain resistant material, which makes a perfect choice for bar tops.
